    "id": "4",
    "title": "The Ethics of Raw Stone",
    "subtitle": "In praise of Brutalism and the enduring truth of unvarnished materials.",
    "summary": "A passionate defense of architectural Brutalism, examining its social ideals and the raw, monumental honesty of concrete, basalt, and granite.",
    "content": [
      "Brutalism is often misunderstood as cold or imposing, a concrete scar on the urban landscape. But the movement's origin—Béton brut, meaning raw concrete—was born of a profound ethical drive. It was a rejection of bourgeois decoration, an insistence on material honesty, and a desire to build monumental public spaces that belonged to everyone.",
      "Raw stone and concrete do not pretend to be anything other than what they are. They carry the marks of the wooden forms that held them, the touch of the hands that poured them, and the gentle weathering of rain and air. In their vast, unpolished surfaces, we find a grounding weight that contrasts beautifully with the ephemeral, glass-and-plastic structures of our digital present."
    ],
